      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5 % on volume-averaged scalar shear stress at worst-case operating point.",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation over three mesh levels (2.1 M, 5.8 M, 14.2 M cells) at the peak-hemolysis point yields GCI = 1.8 % on volume-averaged scalar shear stress. The medium mesh (5.8 M cells) is adopted for all production runs. Criterion met; achieved level equals required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid temperature, flow rate, rotational speed) documented and traceable; MRL 2 requires Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "All five flow-speed operating points were tested in the laboratory at 22 °C, 101.3 kPa, using a glycerol-water blood analogue with documented viscosity. Flow rates were set with a calibrated Coriolis meter (±0.5 % FS). Rotational speed was controlled to ±10 RPM via a closed-loop drive. Conditions are fully documented and traceable. NOTE: test conditions reflect a single laboratory ambient; the operating-theatre deployment envelope (18–26 °C, altitude up to 2 500 m, EMI from adjacent equipment) was not replicated or bounded in any test condition set."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH within ±15 % of experimentally measured RH for each of the five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted RH values at all five operating points fall within ±11 % of measured RH values from the laboratory experiments. Maximum discrepancy is 10.7 % at the 6 L/min, 2 800 RPM point. All comparisons satisfy the ±15 % criterion. Comparisons are made exclusively against data collected at 22 °C laboratory conditions; no comparison data exist for elevated temperature, reduced pressure, or EMI-exposed conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (RH) is directly linked to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis risk) and the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the quantity mandated by FDA guidance for CPB device hemolysis assessment and directly reflects erythrocyte damage. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, scalar stress exposure time) are mechanistically linked to RH via the power-law hemolysis model. QoI relevance is independent of environmental conditions, satisfying the requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same pump geometry, fluid properties, and operating range as the COU; MRL 2 requires Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU device, the same five flow-speed operating points, and a blood analogue fluid whose viscosity is matched to 37 °C whole blood. The COU operating range (2–6 L/min, 2 500–4 000 RPM) is fully covered by the validation dataset. However, the COU deployment environment (operating theatre) introduces temperature, pressure, and EMI conditions not present in the validation activities, creating a gap in environmental relevance that is not acknowledged in the relevance assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations at each operating point; MRL 2 requires Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "All five steady-state simulations were run to mass, momentum, and scalar residuals below 1×10⁻⁵. Torque and pressure-rise monitors were monitored over the final 500 iterations to confirm stationary values. Criterion met at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation plan and independent review of setup inputs documented; MRL 2 requires Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "A simulation plan document was prepared prior to execution, specifying boundary conditions, turbulence model (SST k-ω), hemolysis model coefficients, and post-processing scripts. An independent engineer reviewed the ANSYS Fluent case files against the simulation plan before production runs. No discrepancies were identified. Criterion met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence and hemolysis model forms justified by literature and sensitivity analysis; MRL 2 requires Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model is selected based on its documented performance for rotating-machinery internal flows (Menter 1994; Hariharan et al. 2011). The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al. 1990, coefficients from Heuser & Opitz 1980) is the standard for CFD hemolysis prediction. A sensitivity study varying the hemolysis model exponents by ±10 % showed less than 8 % variation in RH, confirming model-form robustness within the validated parameter space. Model form assessment was conducted at 22 °C; temperature dependence of blood viscosity and its effect on shear-stress-based hemolysis prediction at operating-theatre temperatures was not investigated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions) documented with uncertainty quantification; MRL 2 requires Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry was digitised from the FDA benchmark CAD file (tolerance ±0.01 mm). Fluid density and dynamic viscosity were measured for the glycerol-water analogue at 22 °C (ρ = 1 050 kg/m³, μ = 3.5 mPa·s). Boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, wall rotational speed) are documented with associated measurement uncertainties. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study on the five primary inputs confirmed RH sensitivity is dominated by rotational speed (±2.1 % RH per ±1 % speed). Fluid properties were characterised at 22 °C only; the effect of operating-theatre temperature variation (18–26 °C) on blood analogue viscosity—and consequently on predicted shear stress and RH—was not quantified and is not included in the uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples (pump units used in validation experiments) are representative of the production geometry; MRL 2 requires Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "Two pump units manufactured to the FDA generic centrifugal pump specification were used in the validation experiments. Dimensional inspection confirmed all critical clearances within ±0.02 mm of nominal. Both units produced consistent RH measurements (inter-unit variability < 3 %), confirming sample representativeness. Criterion met at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Computational model input parameters are equivalent to experimental test inputs within stated tolerances; MRL 2 requires Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Computational boundary conditions were set to match experimental measurements: inlet flow rates matched to within ±0.3 % of Coriolis meter readings; rotational speed matched to within ±5 RPM of tachometer readings; outlet pressure matched to within ±0.5 % of transducer readings. Fluid properties in the simulation were set to measured values at 22 °C. Equivalency is demonstrated for all five operating points under laboratory conditions. No equivalency assessment was performed for conditions outside the 22 °C laboratory environment; the computational model does not incorporate temperature- or pressure-dependent fluid property corrections that would be needed to establish equivalency across the full operating-theatre environmental envelope."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels for MRL 2. The six not-assessed factors are within the scope of factors acceptable to defer at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 3. The relative hemolysis index satisfies RH < 1.0 across all five flow-speed operating points. Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under flow and speed conditions matching the COU operating range. The credibility assessment team concludes that the CFD model provides sufficient credibility to support the worst-case hemolysis identification decision for the Class II CPB device. The assessment team notes that all validation data were collected at 22 °C and atmospheric pressure, and that the operating-theatre deployment environment may introduce temperature, pressure, and electromagnetic conditions not covered by the current validation dataset; however, the team assessed that this does not preclude acceptance at MRL 2 given the medium model influence and the corroborating experimental data.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
